Here's an AudioWorkletProcessor implementation for a chorus effect:

```javascript
class ChorusAudioWorkletProcessor extends AudioWorkletProcessor {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.feedback = 0;
    this.delay = 0;
    this.rate = 0;
    this.depth = 0;

    this.delayLine = new Float32Array(48000); // 1 second at 48kHz
    this.delayIndex = 0;
  }

  process(inputs, outputs, parameters) {
    const input = inputs[0];
    const output = outputs[0];

    if (input.length === 0) return true;

    const channelData = input[0];
    const outputChannel = output[0];

    // Get parameter values
    const rate = parameters.rate.length > 0 ? parameters.rate[0] : this.rate;
    const depth = parameters.depth.length > 0 ? parameters.depth[0] : this.depth;
    const delay = parameters.delay.length > 0 ? parameters.delay[0] : this.delay;
    const feedback = parameters.feedback.length > 0 ? parameters.feedback[0] : this.feedback;

    this.rate = rate;
    this.depth = depth;
    this.delay = delay;
    this.feedback = feedback;

    const sampleRate = sampleRate;
    const delaySamples = delay * sampleRate;
    const modulation = Math.sin(2 * Math.PI * rate * currentTime) * depth;

    for (let i = 0; i < channelData.length; i++) {
      const inputSample = channelData[i];

      // Calculate delayed sample with modulation
      const delayTime = delaySamples + modulation * depth;
      const readIndex = (this.delayIndex - delayTime + this.delayLine.length) % this.delayLine.length;

      const delayedSample = this.delayLine[Math.floor(readIndex)];

      // Apply feedback
      const outputSample = inputSample + delayedSample * feedback;

      // Store in delay line
      this.delayLine[this.delayIndex] = inputSample + delayedSample * feedback;
      this.delayIndex = (this.delayIndex + 1) % this.delayLine.length;

      outputChannel[i] = outputSample;
    }

    return true;
  }
}

registerProcessor('chorus-processor', ChorusAudioWorkletProcessor);
```

**Key Parameters:**
- `rate`: LFO frequency (typically 0.1-5 Hz)
- `depth`: Modulation depth (0-1)
- `delay`: Base delay in seconds (typically 0.01-0.05)
- `feedback`: Amount of feedback (0-1)

**To use this processor:**

1. Save the code in a file (e.g., `chorus-processor.js`)
2. In your main JavaScript file:

```javascript
// Load the AudioWorklet
await audioContext.audioWorklet.addModule('chorus-processor.js');

// Create the processor node
const chorusNode = new AudioWorkletNode(audioContext, 'chorus-processor');

// Connect audio source to chorus, then to destination
source.connect(chorusNode);
chorusNode.connect(audioContext.destination);

// Set parameters
chorusNode.parameters.get('rate').value = 0.5;    // 0.5 Hz
chorusNode.parameters.get('depth').value = 0.3;   // 30% depth
chorusNode.parameters.get('delay').value = 0.02;  // 20ms base delay
chorusNode.parameters.get('feedback').value = 0.2; // 20% feedback
```

**Note:** This is a basic implementation. For production use, you might want to add:
- Multi-channel support
- Smooth parameter interpolation
- Better delay line interpolation (linear or cubic)
- Wet/dry mix control
- Error handling

The chorus effect works by creating a delayed copy of the audio signal with a time-varying delay (modulated by an LFO), which creates the characteristic "thickening" and "shimmering" sound.

